  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'mid', 'How does FlatList differ from ScrollView for large data?', '["FlatList virtualizes and renders only visible rows","ScrollView virtualizes; FlatList doesn''t","They are identical","FlatList can''t scroll"]'::jsonb, 0, 'ScrollView renders everything at once; FlatList recycles rows for performance.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'mid', 'How do you handle a tap?', '["Pressable / TouchableOpacity with onPress","addEventListener(''click'')","onClick on a div","a href"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Touchables/Pressable expose onPress for tap handling.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'mid', 'What did the legacy bridge do?', '["Serialize async messages between the JS and native threads","Compile JS to native code","Render the UI on the GPU","Cache network requests"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The old architecture passed JSON messages asynchronously across the bridge.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'mid', 'What is Expo?', '["A framework and tooling on top of React Native","A native iOS language","A bundler","A testing library"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Expo provides build tooling, SDK modules, and OTA updates for RN apps.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'high', 'What does JSI (JavaScript Interface) enable in the New Architecture?', '["Direct synchronous calls between JS and native, replacing the async bridge","A new styling language","Server-side rendering","Automatic memoization"]'::jsonb, 0, 'JSI lets JS hold references to native objects and call them synchronously.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'high', 'What does Fabric replace?', '["The legacy rendering/UIManager layer","The JavaScript engine","The Metro bundler","The navigation library"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Fabric is the New Architecture''s concurrent rendering system.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'high', 'What does the Hermes engine improve?', '["Startup time and memory via bytecode precompilation","Network throughput","CSS parsing","Image decoding"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Hermes is an optimized JS engine that precompiles to bytecode for faster startup.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'high', 'What benefit do TurboModules add?', '["Lazily loaded native modules via JSI","Automatic UI tests","CSS-in-JS support","Offline storage"]'::jsonb, 0, 'TurboModules load native modules on demand and call them through JSI.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'high', 'Why might a long list jank?', '["Heavy render work on the JS thread; fix with virtualization and memoized rows","Too few colors","Using StyleSheet","Using TypeScript"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Expensive per-row rendering on the JS thread drops frames; virtualize and memoize.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'ultra', 'How does the New Architecture remove the bridge bottleneck?', '["JSI allows synchronous, serialization-free JS↔native calls","It moves JS to a worker thread","It caches all native calls","It compiles JS ahead of time"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Instead of async JSON messaging, JSI exposes native methods directly to JS.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'ultra', 'What computes layout off the main thread?', '["The shadow tree (Yoga)","The JS event loop","The GPU shader","The network stack"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Yoga calculates the shadow tree''s layout on a background thread before committing.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'ultra', 'How does Reanimated keep gestures/animations at 60fps?', '["It runs animation worklets on the UI thread, off the JS thread","It precomputes all frames","It uses CSS transitions","It disables the bridge"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Reanimated executes worklets on the UI thread so animations don''t depend on JS thread availability.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'ultra', 'What does codegen produce in the New Architecture?', '["Type-safe native interface code from JS spec files","Optimized images","Minified JS","Test fixtures"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Codegen generates the C++/native glue for TurboModules and Fabric components from TS specs.'),
  ('React Native', 'Frontend & Mobile', 'ultra', 'Roughly how long is one frame''s budget at 60fps?', '["About 16ms","About 100ms","About 1ms","About 60ms"]'::jsonb, 0, '60fps means ~16.7ms per frame; exceeding it on JS or UI thread drops frames.'),
